title: application-gateway-create-probe-classic-ps
content:
# Create a Custom Probe for Azure Application Gateway (Classic) using PowerShell

This documentation provides instructions on how to create a custom probe for an Azure Application Gateway using PowerShell in the classic deployment model. Custom probes are useful for applications that have specific health check pages or do not provide a successful response on the default web application.

**NOTE:** This document discusses configuration through the Azure Portal. Please _always_ use infrastructure-as-code (IaC) for production environments and deploy through Azure DevOps pipelines.

## Prerequisites

Before proceeding with the steps, ensure that you have the following prerequisites in place:

- Azure PowerShell module installed
- Azure subscription and resource group created

## Create an Application Gateway

To create an application gateway, follow these steps:

1. Create an application gateway resource.
2. Create a configuration XML file or a configuration object.
3. Commit the configuration to the newly created application gateway resource.

### Create an Application Gateway Resource with a Custom Probe

To create the gateway, use the `New-AzureApplicationGateway` cmdlet, replacing the values with your own. 

```powershell
New-AzureApplicationGateway -Name AppGwTest -VnetName testvnet1 -Subnets @("Subnet-1")
```

To validate that the gateway was created, you can use the `Get-AzureApplicationGateway` cmdlet.

```powershell
Get-AzureApplicationGateway AppGwTest
```

### Configure an Application Gateway using XML

You can use an XML file to configure all application gateway settings and commit them to the application gateway resource. 

1. Copy the following XML text to Notepad.

```xml
<ApplicationGatewayConfiguration xmlns:i="https://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/windowsazure">
<FrontendIPConfigurations>
    <FrontendIPConfiguration>
        <Name>fip1</Name>
        <Type>Private</Type>
    </FrontendIPConfiguration>
</FrontendIPConfigurations>
<FrontendPorts>
    <FrontendPort>
        <Name>port1</Name>
        <Port>80</Port>
    </FrontendPort>
</FrontendPorts>
<Probes>
    <Probe>
        <Name>Probe01</Name>
        <Protocol>Http</Protocol>
        <Host>contoso.com</Host>
        <Path>/path/custompath.htm</Path>
        <Interval>15</Interval>
        <Timeout>15</Timeout>
        <UnhealthyThreshold>5</UnhealthyThreshold>
    </Probe>
    </Probes>
    <BackendAddressPools>
    <BackendAddressPool>
        <Name>pool1</Name>
        <IPAddresses>
            <IPAddress>1.1.1.1</IPAddress>
            <IPAddress>2.2.2.2</IPAddress>
```

2. Save the file with a ".xml" extension.

3. Use the `Set-AzureApplicationGatewayConfig` cmdlet to configure the application gateway with the XML file.

```powershell
Set-AzureApplicationGatewayConfig -Name AppGwTest -ConfigPath "C:\path\to\config.xml"
```

4. Commit the configuration to the application gateway.

```powershell
Set-AzureApplicationGateway -Name AppGwTest
```

This will apply the custom probe configuration to the application gateway.

You have now successfully created a custom probe for Azure Application Gateway using PowerShell in the classic deployment model.
